<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1439,1945]" box="[198,1407,1599,1625]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Etymology. From the Latin, 
<emphasis box="[532,617,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">crispus</emphasis>
, relating to the sinuous, curly hairs of the posterior parapenicillum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1439,1945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Geographical distribution. Known only from the Magdalena River valley in Antioquia, 
<collectingCountry box="[1254,1370,1639,1665]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="14.[151,255,1684,1708]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,597,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,597,1657]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 26. Leurotrigona, geographic records. The arrow indicates L. crispula sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/185352/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,184,1679,1705]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1439,1945]" box="[198,390,1719,1745]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Nest. Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1439,1945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Discussion. 
<taxonomicName box="[345,606,1759,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leurotrigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[345,606,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Leurotrigona crispula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[617,714,1759,1785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[617,707,1759,1785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[943,1057,1759,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leurotrigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[943,1057,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">L. pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whose workers share the very small size, the general shape of the head and all other characters listed in Diagnosis, except the vestiture of the clypeus and lower parocular area, which is longer and more abundant than in 
<taxonomicName box="[1062,1174,1839,1864]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leurotrigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[1062,1174,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">L. pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Also, the males present remarkable differences in the shape of pre-genital sterna and genitalia that can be seen comparing the figures 
<number box="[207,265,1919,1945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" value="8.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="6.0">6–10</number>
(
<taxonomicName box="[283,410,1919,1944]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leurotrigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[283,410,1919,1944]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">L. crispula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[417,508,1919,1945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[417,503,1919,1945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
) and 
<number box="[577,648,1919,1945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" value="13.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="11.0">11–15</number>
(
<taxonomicName box="[666,777,1919,1944]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leurotrigona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[666,777,1919,1944]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">L. pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
